🔵What is JavaScript ? 
JavaScript is programming language that makes web pages interactive
JavaScript is synchronous and single-threaded by nature, but it can handle asynchronous operations 
using browser APIs and the event loop.

Think of a website like a car:

HTML = structure (body of car)
CSS = design (color, styling)
JavaScript = engine (makes it move)

Example:

Button click → show popup
Form submit → validate input
Scroll → load more data

🔵How JavaScript Works in the Browser

JavaScript itself is single-threaded & synchronous (by default) - code run line by line.
That means:
It can do one thing at a time
It has one Call Stack
It executes code line by line

>> What is V8?
V8 is Google’s JavaScript engine used in: chrome, edge

Its job:
Parse JS code
Convert to machine code

Read JS code
Parse it
Compile it
Execute it

Inside V8:
🔵when JavaScript code run then divide into two phase
JavaScript code run hota hai
            ↓
Execution Context create hota hai
            ↓ 
Execution Context ke 2 phases:
            ↓ 
1. Memory Creation Phase
   - variables → undefined
   - functions → memory me store (only reference not whole fn)

2. Code Execution Phase
   - code line by line execute
   - function call hone par
     uska execution context
     call stack me aata hai     

Memory Heap → stores variables / objects
Call Stack → executes functions

>> Call Stack (LIFO)
LIFO = Last In First Out
A stack where functions are executed.

JavaScript engine does NOT have built-in timers, DOM, fetch, etc.
Browser provides them.

Examples:
setTimeout()
setInterval()
DOM events (click)
fetch()
localStorage
Geolocation
These are called Web APIs

>> Callback Queue (Macrotask Queue)
When async tasks finish, callback goes to queue.
FIFO = First In First Out

Examples:
setTimeout
setInterval
DOM click events

Event Loop
The Event Loop watches:
Is Call Stack empty?
If YES:
➡️ Takes first callback from queue
➡️ Pushes into Call Stack
This repeats forever.

Example:
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => {
   console.log("Timer");
}, 0);

console.log("End");


Step 1: console.log("Start"); ---------------- Runs immediately.
Step 2: setTimeout(...)       ---------------- Moves to Web API timer.
Step 3: console.log("End");   ---------------- Runs immediately.
Step 4: Timer complete → callback enters queue. 
Step 5: Stack empty → Event Loop pushes callback. 


                    JS Code
                        ↓
                    JavaScript Engine
                        ↓
                    Call Stack executes synchronous code
                        ↓
                    Async tasks go to Web APIs
                        ↓
                    Completed callbacks move to Queue
                        ↓
                    Event Loop checks stack
                        ↓
                    Moves callback to stack when empty


🔵Var vs Let vs Const

variables means it is container used to store any data/value.
and datatype means what type of value stored in that container like string num etc

var - old way, function scoped, re-declare allowed
let - blocked scoped, not re-declare, only update
const - block scoped, not re-declare, not update

| Feature    | var           | let     | const   |
| ---------- | ------------- | ------- | ------- |
| Scope      | function      | block   | block   |
| Re-declare | ✅             | ❌       | ❌       |
| Update     | ✅             | ✅       | ❌       |
| Hoisting   | ✅ (undefined) | ✅ (TDZ) | ✅ (TDZ) |

📦 SCOPE IN JAVASCRIPT
👉 Scope means:
Accessibility + Visibility of variables

Yani:
Kis variable ko kaha se access/use kar sakte ho.

1. Global Scope
Pure program me accessible

let hero = "Shaktimaan";

function room1() {
  console.log(hero); // ✅ accessible
}

function room2() {
  console.log(hero); // ✅ accessible
}

room1();
room2();


2. Function Scope
Variable sirf function ke andar accessible

Example 1:
function room() {
  let secret = "Chocolate";
  console.log(secret); // ✅ accessible
}

room();

// console.log(secret); ❌ Error
// Kyuki secret function ke bahar visible nahi hai

Example 2:
function hello() {
    var name = "John";
    if (true) {
        var age = 20;
    }
    console.log(name); // works
    console.log(age);  // also works
}
hello();

3. Block Scope
let & const sirf { } ke andar accessible

Example 1:
{
  let money = 5000;
  console.log(money); // ✅ accessible
}

// console.log(money); ❌ Error

Example 2:
function hello() {
    if (true) {
        let age = 20;
        console.log(age); // works
    }
    console.log(age); // ERROR
}

hello();


4. Lexical Scope: When inner function access the outer function variable is called lexical scope
Inner function outer function ki cheeze access kar sakta hai

function father() {
  let car = "BMW";

  function son() {
    console.log(car); // ✅ accessible
  }

  son();
}

father();

🎬 SUMMARY

1. Global Scope
   → Har jagah accessible

2. Function Scope
   → Sirf function ke andar accessible

3. Block Scope
   → Sirf { } block ke andar accessible

4. Lexical Scope
   → Inner function outer variable access kar sakta hai


console.log(a);
var a  = 10;                // undefined

console.log(a);
let a = 10                  // reference error

🔵Hoisting means JavaScript allocates memory for variable and functions before execution.
TDZ: variable present in memory but not usable is callled Tdz


🔵Primitive data types like string, number, boolean, null, undefined, bigint, and symbol are immutable.
Non-primitive types like objects and arrays are mutable by default because their internal data can be modified.

immutable -- data cannot chagne
mutable   -- data can chagne

🔵What is Type Coercion in JavaScript?
JavaScript automatically converts one data type into another data type while performing operations or comparisons.
Types of Type Coercion:
1. Implicit Coercion (Automatic)  "10" + 5
2. Explicit Coercion (Manual)     Number("10") + 5

console.log("5" + 1);   // 51
console.log("5" - 1);   // 4
console.log(true + 1);  // 2
console.log(5 == "5");  // true
console.log(5 === "5"); // false

